{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"28857d7e-15c5-4b07-8d37-3efecbdae267","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n---\n\n**1. Recursive glob with `**\\*.*`** (line 9, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThis forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. As the repo grows, this becomes increasingly expensive. Prefer explicit paths or narrower globs (e.g., `*.txt`).\n\n---\n\n**2. File I/O via property function** (line 13, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` during evaluation performs synchronous disk I/O on every evaluation pass. This blocks the evaluator and cannot be cached.\n\n---\n\n**3. Deeply chained `<Import>` files** (`level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props`)\nEach import adds an evaluation pass. Three levels is mild, but this pattern scales poorly—if more layers are added it compounds with the other issues. Flattening where possible reduces evaluation depth.\n\n---\n\n**Summary of recommendations:**\n| Issue | Fix |\n|-------|-----|\n| `**\\*.*` glob | Narrow to specific extensions/directories |\n| `File::ReadAllText` in property | Move to a target (runs at build-time, not eval-time) |\n| Chained imports | Flatten into fewer files when practical |\n\nThe biggest offenders are #1 and #2—both perform expensive I/O during every project evaluation (IDE load, restore, build).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c3a071a5-a0da-42a9-8c15-8da688960b6d","outputTokens":406,"requestId":"5C44:2F61F4:5EE150C:67F374B:69F15D16"},"id":"ded165c8-704c-44c2-a712-163bdfbf0079","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:21:40.624Z","parentId":"3c6c8a3b-ca94-4669-b991-b3fe73833210"}
